Editorial Reviews

Review

Praise for previous books in the Warriors series: In the style of classics by Tolkien or Jacques. Youll never look at your plain old tabby the same way again. -- Cleveland Plain Dealer

The author has created an intriguing world with an intricate structure and mythology, and an engaging young hero. -- School Library Journal

Tension-filled. -- ALA Booklist

From the Inside Flap

ThunderClan's darkest hour is upon them, as Tigerstar's quest for power plunges all the Clans into the most terrible danger any cat has ever faced. In order to save his Clan and his friends, Fireheart must uncover the meaning of an ominous proclamation from StarClan:

Four will become two. Lion and tiger will meet in battle, and blood will rule the forest.

The time has come for prophecies to unfold, and for heroes to rise ...

--School Library Journa

From the Back Cover

ThunderClan's darkest hour is upon them, as Tigerstar's quest for power plunges all the Clans into the most terrible danger any cat has ever faced. In order to save his Clan and his friends, Fireheart must uncover the meaning of an ominous proclamation from StarClan:

"Four will become two. Lion and tiger will meet in battle, and blood will rule the forest."

The time has come for prophecies to unfold, and for heroes to rise ...

About the Author

Erin Hunter is inspired by a love of cats and a fascination with the ferocity of the natural world. In addition to having great respect for nature in all its forms, Erin enjoys creating rich mythical explanations for animal behavior. She is also the author of the Seekers, Survivors, Bravelands, and Bamboo Kingdom series.

How are ratings calculated?
To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzes reviews to verify trustworthiness.

Spencer palmer
5.0 out of 5 stars A grand finale to The Prophecies Begins arc
Reviewed in the United States on September 19, 2021
Verified Purchase
My likes are that first, this is the first Warriors books that I have ever read when I was a teenager, second its nice to reread the book again, third I love the romances between Firestar and Sandstorm, fourth l like the final battle against Bloodclan, fifth as a teenager I was thrilled that Brightheart has go her new name, sixth I enjoy the receiving of the nine lives ceremony, and finally I am happy to reread and relive the original series of Warriors.

My dislikes are that it was full of gore (my first reaction to reading the book as a teenager), second like hated Darkstripe, one of villains in the original Warriors series and I was glad that he was killed off by the last pages of the book,(though I wished that Firestar killed him instead of Graystripe, but that is what friends are for), third as a teenager I was disappointed that Tigerstar and Firestar did not fight each other in the finale, but when I became an adult and read The Last Hope I was thrilled that the two characters got their final battle, fourth I did not like Bonehill and that is where my teenager reading reaction for gore came from, fifth I did not like the murder of Stonefur, sixth I wished that Firestar was able to help Tawnypaw more so that she wouldnt join Shadowclan, but I have come to terms with her choice, seventh I had wished that Fireheart before he became Firestar told the clans about Yellofang as Brokenstars mother and compare the similarities between Graystripe and Bluestars For bidden romance with Riverclan, and finally I was saddened by Whitestorms death.

My full review is that I have enjoyed rereading the original series of the Warriors, rereading this book got to see why this one of the favorite Warrior series books that readers will read more, and it was a satisfying conclusion which is why I am giving this book a 5 star rating.

Amazon Customer
5.0 out of 5 stars The best
Reviewed in the United Kingdom on September 20, 2019
Verified Purchase
I love this book so much. Cats are one of my favourite animals, and they are so beautifully portrayed here. The plot is lovely, with twists and turns, romance, action, sub-plots, and most importantly, loveable, loveable characters. Firestar is my favourite character, and this is my favourite book in the best arc.

A small house cat named Rusty goes into the forest, meeting clan cats who offer him a place in the clan. He accepts, and soon finds himself in ThunderClan, an apprentice. He befriends 2 other apprentices, Ravenpaw and Graypaw. However, the dastardly Tigerclaw is soon made deputy, and Firepaw is sure he is up to something. Over the next few books, Tigerclaw is outcast for his crimes, and Fireheart is made deputy. The clan leader is shocked by his betrayal, but worse is to come. Tigerstar is now leader of ShadowClan, setting a dog pack on ThunderClan. ThunderClan win, but their leader dies, making Firestar the new leader. This book covers his leadership, and I love it. Greatly recommended.
